1. strength of tDCS effects is determined by current density and duration (p.207, 218).

2. Polarity and position of electrodes may lead to different effects (p. 207).

3. Appropriate electrode material and method of application minimize unwanted electrical phenomena( p. 217).

4. Focality of stimulation can to some extent be controlled and may impact stimulation effects (p. 217).

5. Blinding of subjects to tDCS conditions is crucial; ramping up the current is most important factor controlling sensation (p. 217).

6. Traits and state (mental/cortical) of subjects influence the efficacy of tDCS (p. 218).

7. Only a few seconds of tDCS can already cause changes in neural excitability (p. 218).

8. After-effects of stimulation can be elicited after 10 minutes of tDCS (p. 218).

9. Repeated application of tDCS may stabilize these induced changes (p.218).

10. Safety of current protocols is increasingly established, but be cautions when deviating from them or using clinical populations (p.219).

