@article{Stagg2011b,
abstract = {Since the rediscovery of transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) about 10 years ago, interest in tDCS has grown exponentially. A noninvasive stimulation technique that induces robust excitability changes within the stimulated cortex, tDCS is increasingly being used in proof-of-principle and stage IIa clinical trials in a wide range of neurological and psychiatric disorders. Alongside these clinical studies, detailed work has been performed to elucidate the mechanisms underlying the observed effects. In this review, the authors bring together the results from these pharmacological, neurophysiological, and imaging studies to describe their current knowledge of the physiological effects of tDCS. In addition, the theoretical framework for how tDCS affects motor learning is proposed.},
annote = {Tagline
[title]

Subject
Reviews tDCS physiology at a cellular/systems scale, with an emphasis on neuropharmacology. Provides brief primer on synaptic plasticity, neuromodulation and tDCS history / early studies into excitability. In-depth treatment of human studies where the canonical MEP amlitude increase/decreases folllowing anodal/cathodal stimulation are probed under administration of various pharmacological agents.

Key findings
During-stimulation effects can be wholly explained in terms of membrane potential modulations. Calcium/sodium channel blockers abolishn anodal immediate and after-effects, but not cathodal.

Anodal after-effects depend upon NDMAR activity. GABA concentration as measured by MRS increases after anodal tDCS.

Cathodal after-effects are also abolished by NMDAR antagonists, and lead to MRS-measured decreases in glutamate.

Outstanding questions
The paper also discusses a whole bunch of neuromodulatory effects. Almost every catecholamine-drug seems to do something, but the effects are very idiosyncratic.

Offers a neat model of tDCS-mediated motor learning effects, but this is still somewhat speculative.

As the authors note, one reason tDCS mechanisms are still unclear is that there is a shortage of animal studies. This still appears to very much be a problem today.

Significance
Probably the most thorough overview of the cellular mechanisms of tDCS; highly recommended to read through again and mine the references.

