}
@article{Whyte2014,
abstract = {Comments on an article by Aurore Thibaut et al. (see record 2014-12687-004). The article by Thibaut et al. examines the effects of a single session of anodal transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS), delivered to individuals with DOC for 20minutes over the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex, on level of consciousness. In this double-blind sham-controlled crossover study, patients demonstrated systematically higher levels of consciousness, as measured by the Coma Recovery Scale-Revised, shortly after the tDCS treatment than before it or before or after the sham session. The authors hypothesize that the treatment may have enhanced attention and working memory processes that underlie many conscious tasks. Of interest, this improvement was significant for those in MCS at baseline but not those in VS. Treatments that are effective only in neurologically defined subsamples are even more challenging, due to the large number who need to be screened to identify eligible subjects. Studies like the one by Thibaut et al., however, may offer one way out of this dilemma. If a longer course of tDCS can accelerate recovery for a subgroup of the DOC population, perhaps a positive response to a single session of tDCS can identify the subgroup of individuals who are treatment responders to this or to other treatments that modulate attention and working memory circuitry. If so, tDCS may provide a useful screening approach for other treatment studies, as well as a useful treatment in its own right. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2014 APA, all rights reserved)},
